Ad Exposure on Instagram: A Visual Story

Jason Thaing

Introduction

This visual data story explores the experience of Instagram users during 5-minute scrolling sessions. Each session was logged using a Google Form and includes the number of ads seen, the most common ad category, time of day, and the device used. In total, 42 scrolling sessions were recorded.

The goal was to investigate whether ad exposure varies across different contexts such as time of day, device type, or user behaviour.

Google Form

From my previous form, I added a new section asking what type of device was used during the Instagram session (e.g.smartphone, tablet, or desktop/laptop). I included this because the layout and ad delivery on Instagram can be dis-similar on each device. For example, users on smartphones may encounter more frequent or differently formatted ads compared to those on a desktop. By recording this detail, Ill be more able to explore whether device type influences the number or type of ads observed.

What Time of Day Has the Most Ads?

Bar chart showing average number of ads seen across different times of day

Users reported different ad loads depending on the time of day. Sessions during Morning (6am12pm) and Afternoon (12pm6pm) periods tended to have higher ad counts, indicating that Instagram may push more ad content when users are most active. On average, 20.3 ads were shown during each 5-minute scroll.

Do Devices Affect What Ads Are Shown?

Facet bar chart showing most common ad category per device used

This facetted bar chart shows the most common ad category by device. For example, Tech/Gadgets appeared most frequently on smartphones, However Tech/Gadgets was also most common on desktops, This suggests there is influence of device type on the targeting of ads.

Are Ads Increasing Over Time?

Line chart showing total ads seen per day over time

By converting timestamps to dates, we visualized total ad volume per day. The trend provides insight into whether ad exposure increases or fluctuates over time. For an example spikes may align with content activity, algorithm changes, or even user behaviour. In our case we see a positive linear slope as the date progresses suggesting there could have been a algorithm change or a change user behaviour.

Conclusion

These visualisations tell story: Instagrams ad exposure isnt completely random its shaped by when, how, and on what you scroll. These patterns, although based on a small sample, hint at underlying platform strategies and personalization algorithms.

All plots were created using ggplot2, and code used only STATS 220 techniques. The colour palette and styling were designed to reflect Instagrams brand identity.
